<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n01080c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n01" href="#n01080c">N01 (VI.B.10)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n01all.htm#n01080c"> 80(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> mirth provoking</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[Pantomime and Variety. / &ldquo;Robinson Crusoe&rdquo; at the Queen&apos;s]</font> All the comedy parts were very well taken by sprightly comedians, Barrett McDonnell, as Will Atkins, a bold buccaneer, being quite a fearsome villain, and Stanley Granby and Frank Grant, in the respective parts of the skipper and mate of the &ldquo;Saucy Sall&rdquo;y, very strong both in song and patter. The Billy Crusoe of Jim Johnson was also <mark>mirth-provoking</mark>, and even more laughable was the Mrs. Crusoe of Gus Walker, a typical pantomime dame. <small> <a name="IT19dec22" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#IT19dec22"><cite title="source">Irish Times</cite></a> (19 December 1922) 9/7</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c05143c" href="c05all.htm#c05143c">VI.C.05:143(c)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
